There are approximately 600 Kashima Shrines nationwide, concentrated primarily in the {{ill|Tōhoku region|ja|東北地方|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and the {{ill|Kantō region|ja|関東地方|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, with the head shrine being {{ill|Kashima Jingū|ja|鹿島神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Kashima, Ibaraki|ja|鹿嶋市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Ibaraki Prefecture|ja|茨城県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Most of these shrines were established by inviting the deity from Kashima Jingū, worshipping the same deity, Takemikazuchi.
Takemikazuchi, together with {{ill|Futsunushi|ja|経津主神|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of {{ill|Katori Jingū|ja|香取神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Katori, Chiba|ja|香取市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Chiba Prefecture|ja|千葉県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), was revered by the Imperial court and central aristocracy as the ancestral deity of the {{ill|Nakatomi clan|ja|中臣氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Fujiwara clan|ja|藤原氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Being a god of martial prowess, Takemikazuchi was also worshipped by samurai families ('''Kashima belief''').
