'''Kashima Shrine''' (鹿島神社, [[Kyujitai]]: 鹿嶋神社) is a type of Shinto shrine named "Kashima" dedicated to the deity {{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|タケミカヅチ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takemikazuchi|qq=}}.
There are approximately 600 Kashima Shrines nationwide, concentrated primarily in the {{ill|Tōhoku region|ja|東北地方|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tōhoku region|qq=}} and the {{ill|Kantō region|ja|関東地方|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kantō region|qq=}}, with the head shrine being {{ill|Kashima Jingu|lt=Kashima Jingu|lt=Kashima Jingū|ja|鹿島神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kashima Jingū|qq=}} in {{ill|Kashima, Ibaraki|ja|鹿嶋市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kashima, Ibaraki|qq=}}, {{ill|Ibaraki Prefecture|ja|茨城県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ibaraki Prefecture|qq=}}. Most of these shrines were established by inviting the deity from Kashima Jingū, worshipping the same deity, Takemikazuchi.
Takemikazuchi, together with {{ill|Futsunushi|ja|経津主神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Futsunushi|qq=}} of {{ill|Katori Jingū|ja|香取神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Katori Jingū|qq=}} ({{ill|Katori, Chiba|ja|香取市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Katori, Chiba|qq=}}, {{ill|Chiba Prefecture|ja|千葉県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chiba Prefecture|qq=}}), was revered by the Imperial court and central aristocracy as the ancestral deity of the {{ill|Nakatomi clan|ja|中臣氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakatomi clan|qq=}} and {{ill|Fujiwara clan|ja|藤原氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fujiwara clan|qq=}}. Being a god of martial prowess, Takemikazuchi was also worshipped by samurai families ('''Kashima belief''').
